body:
Long time user of webpack, got into the same problem with mini-css-extract-plugin. Spent some time and this is what I found. My knowledge of Webpack internals is far too superficial to fully  understand it, but I hope it will be of some help to somebody more knowledgeable than myself.

The problem (in mini-css-extract-plugin) lies in `loader.js` around line 160;

```javascript
text = text.map(line => {
  const module = findModuleById(compilation.modules, line[0]);
  return {
    identifier: module.identifier(),
    content: line[1],
    media: line[2],
    sourceMap: line[3]
  };
});
```
The problem is that `line[0]` contains `undefined`, so `module` is `null`

The `text` is actually a `module.exports` coming from the following (line 52 of `loader.js`):

```javascript
const exec = (loaderContext, code, filename) => {
  const module = new _module.default(filename, loaderContext);
  module.paths = _module.default._nodeModulePaths(loaderContext.context); // eslint-disable-line no-underscore-dangle
  module.filename = filename;
  module._compile(code, filename); // eslint-disable-line no-underscore-dangle
  return module.exports;
};

// _module is defined as follows:

var _module = _interopRequireDefault(require("module"));
function _interopRequireDefault(obj) { return obj && obj.__esModule ? obj : { default: obj }; }
```
Up to 4.31.0, the `module.exports` contains a list of of lists, the first element of the first list (the `line[0]` above) being `0`.
Once we get to 4.32.0 the first element of the first list is `undefined`.

This is as far as I could get, and as said already - I am not knowledgeable enough to go deeper.
Maybe a problem with the way the module identifier is handled for ES modules ? Wild guessing ...
Cheers !
